title: Network Degree
description: Exploring network degree of armed conflict dataset
contents:
Assignment 3 description
Identify network format
Describe and identify nodes and edges
Provide statistics related to centrality and degree
Interpret network density and centralization measures


knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = FALSE)

library(igraph)
library(stringr)
library(tidyverse)
library(network)
library(ggplot2)
library(visNetwork)






Checking density of network
The code for checking the density of our network is as shown. The
argument ‘loops’ is set to false because it is not possible for a
Government or party to be involved in conflict with itself

[1] 0.03821352

The graph density value indicates that ~3.8% of all possible ties in
the network are completed.
Degree
Now, the objective is to find the degree of each node. The degree of
a node indicates its centrality or popularity in the network. In this
case, a high degree would signify the country being involved in a higher
number of conflicts.


knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE)

graph.nodes<-data.frame(name=V(graph)$name,
degree=igraph::degree(graph))

graph.nodes<-graph.nodes %>%
mutate(indegree=igraph::degree(graph, mode="in",loops=FALSE),
outdegree=igraph::degree(graph, mode="out",loops=FALSE))



In-degree and out-degree
histograms


knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE)

hist(graph.nodes$indegree, main="Conflicts: In-degree Distribution", xlab="Number of conflict episodes")






hist(graph.nodes$outdegree, main="Climate Influence: Out-degree Distribution ", xlab="Number of conflict episodes")




Due to the structure of this network, the Governments involved in the
conflict have outgoing edges, while rebel groups involved in conflict
with the Government have incoming edges. Hence, all the outdegree
numbers are from the Government side, which signifies the number of
different rebel groups the particular Government had to fight - while
all the indegree numbers refer to rebel groups, which signifies the
number of Governments fought by the rebel group. Since the number of
rebel groups is much higher than number of Governments, the histograms
values for indegree and outdegree are skewed towards that of the rebel
groups. For example, out-degrees are concentrated around 0 since all
rebel groups have values only for in-degrees, and hence have 0
out-degree. The in-degree histogram shows more variation as it captures
the in-degree of all rebel groups.

title: Network Structure
description: Exploring structure of armed conflict dataset
contents:
library(igraph)
library(stringr)
library(tidyverse)
library(network)
library(ggplot2)
library(visNetwork)



Assignment 2 tasks
Describe network data size and attributes
Analyze dyad and triad census
Understand local/global transitivity of the network
Loading the dataset
I have read in the dataset and subset it to only include observations
and columns that will be important in analyzing intrastate
conflicts in the Asian subcontinent.
In the UCDP dataset, an intrastate conflict is defined as a conflict
wherein one of the sides is the Government of a country and the other
side is a rebel group or militant faction, without external support from
any other country’s Governments.
The dataset is thus structured such that the first 2 columns are the
‘from’ nodes, which in this case are Governments of countries involved
in the conflict, and ‘to’ nodes, which includes rebel groups and
militant factions that the Governments had conflicts with, respectively.
Numerical IDs of these variables can be dropped as they do not help in
interpreting the analysis. Secondary parties in the conflicts can also
be dropped, as intrastate conflicts do not involve any secondary power
providing support to either side of the conflict.
After carrying out basic pre-processing and subsetting of the data, I
proceed to convert it into an edge list, to carry out my network based
analysis.
Network structure and
attributes
The code used for understanding the network structure is as shown
below


knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE)
vcount(graph)


[1] 159

ecount(graph)


[1] 960

igraph::vertex_attr_names(graph)


[1] "name"

igraph::edge_attr_names(graph)


 [1] "incompatibility"  "territory_name"   "year"            
 [4] "intensity_level"  "type_of_conflict" "start_date"      
 [7] "start_prec"       "start_date2"      "start_prec2"     
[10] "dyad_id"          "conflict_id"      "location"        

igraph::vertex_attr_names(graph)


[1] "name"

igraph::edge_attr_names(graph)


 [1] "incompatibility"  "territory_name"   "year"            
 [4] "intensity_level"  "type_of_conflict" "start_date"      
 [7] "start_prec"       "start_date2"      "start_prec2"     
[10] "dyad_id"          "conflict_id"      "location"        

The edge list created from a the relevant subset of the conflict data
results in a node count of 159 and edge count of 960. Each edge between
a Government and a rebel group represents a conflict that caused at
least 25 deaths in a calendar year (referred to as an ‘episode’ of
conflict).
Hence, the edge is labelled with the year of the conflict, as well as
the territory of conflict, together constituting the ‘episode’. This is
an directed graph.
Dyad census and Triad census
The code used for understanding the dyad and triad census is as shown
below


knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE)
igraph::dyad.census(graph) 


$mut
[1] 0

$asym
[1] 960

$null
[1] 11601

igraph::triad.census(graph)


 [1] 635702   4804  15431   1413      9      0      0      0      0
[10]      0      0      0      0      0      0      0

is_directed(graph)


[1] TRUE

is_weighted(graph)


[1] FALSE

is_bipartite(graph)


[1] FALSE

Since it is a directed graph, there are no mutual edges, and all 960
edges are asymmetric. There are a total of 216976 null edges. The
directed nature of the graph is also confirmed as shown above.
Transitivity and clustering


knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE)
transitivity(graph)


[1] 0

From the transitivity score of 0, it is clear that none of the
connected triads are transitive, which is, none of the triads have all
three links present between the nodes.


knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE)

transitivity(graph, type="local",vids = V(graph)[c("Government of India","Government of China", "Government of Pakistan")])


[1] 0 0 0

On checking the local transitivity for 3 nodes (Government of India,
Pakistan and China), it becomes clear that transitivity can not be
computed for this network. The reason is that transitivity works only on
undirected graphs. The package warning also mentions that the
transitivity result is likely incorrect in case there are multiple edges
between the same pair of vertices. Due to the structure of the conflict
network, wherein there are very often multiple edges between the same 2
vertices denoting a new episode of the conflict, transitivity is not a
useful metric for this network.
Path lengths


knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE)
average.path.length(graph,directed=T)


[1] 1

names(igraph::components(graph))


[1] "membership" "csize"      "no"        

igraph::components(graph)$no


[1] 12

igraph::components(graph)$csize


 [1] 40 41 33  4  6  8  4  2  3  3  5 10

After subsetting, this graph contains 12 components of varying sizes.
The smallest component has a size of 2, and the largest component has 40
nodes.
Some network visualizations


knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE)

m1 <- layout_nicely(graph)
w1 <- E(graph)$names
plot(graph, 
        vertex.label.color = "blue", 
        edge.color = 'black',
        edge.width = w1,
        layout = m1)






knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE)
vn <- toVisNetworkData(graph)

visNetwork(nodes = vn$nodes, edges = vn$edges, height = "1000px", width = "100%") %>%
  visOptions(highlightNearest = TRUE) %>% 
  visLegend(enabled = TRUE,position = 'right') %>%
  visInteraction(multiselect = TRUE, navigationButtons=TRUE,dragNodes=TRUE,dragView=TRUE,zoomView=TRUE, hideEdgesOnZoom = TRUE, hideEdgesOnDrag = TRUE,hoverConnectedEdges = TRUE) %>%
  visEdges(label = vn$edges$title, physics = FALSE,labelHighlightBold = TRUE, color = vn$edges$color) %>%
  visNodes(shape = 'dot', label = vn$nodes$label, title = vn$nodes$id, labelHighlightBold = TRUE, borderWidth = 1.25, borderWidthSelected = 1.75)

title: Introduction - Network analysis of armed conflict
contents:
Armed conflicts network
analysis
The objective of this project is to use network analysis methods to
examine armed conflicts data. Conflict, from interpersonal disputes to
armed conflicts between states, has always been an inherent part of
human civilization at some level. This is especially relevant today, as
recent world events serve as an extremely unpleasant reminder of the
tragic destruction of human life and livelihood due to armed conflicts.
This project aims to analyze historical data on armed and violent
conflicts in the time period from 1946 - 2020.
Data source
This project uses the Uppsala Conflict Data Program’s (UCDP) Dyadic
Dataset, a project within the UCDP at the Department of Peace and
Conflict Research, Uppsala University. The UCDP Dyadic dataset builds on
the UCDP/PRIO Armed Conflict dataset, by focusing on individual dyads
within each conflict. For the purpose of data collection, state-based
armed conflict is defined as: “a contested incompatibility that concerns
government and/or territory where the use of armed force between two
parties, of which at least one is the government of a state, results in
at least 25 battle-related deaths in a calendar year”
Data downloads - Pettersson, Therese (2021) UCDP Dyadic Dataset
Codebook v 21.1 (https://ucdp.uu.se/downloads/)
